{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:18:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:18:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14620"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14620","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14620"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.1,0.06,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7313"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14620"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1225"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3478"},{"type":"tags","id":"3630"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"8831"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of severe headache, fever, neck pain, and photophobia. She appears confused and drowsy. She has a history of splenectomy following trauma five years ago and takes penicillin prophylaxis. She works as a primary school teacher.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears severely unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 39.2\u00b0C. She has marked neck stiffness and is photophobic. There is no rash. Her chest is clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA lumbar puncture is performed and cerebrospinal fluid microscopy reveals gram negative diplococci.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative organism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Neisseria meningitidis","Streptococcus pneumoniae","Haemophilus influenzae","Listeria monocytogenes","Escherichia coli"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of bacterial meningitis, and the finding of gram negative diplococci on CSF microscopy is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003ENeisseria meningitidis\u003C/strong\u003E infection. \u003Cem\u003EN. meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E is the leading cause of bacterial meningitis in young adults and is particularly common in those with close contact with children. The patient\u0027s history of splenectomy puts her at significantly increased risk of infection with encapsulated organisms, including \u003Cem\u003EN. meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/strong\u003E is also a common cause of bacterial meningitis and is another encapsulated organism that poses increased risk to post-splenectomy patients. However, it appears as gram positive diplococci on microscopy, which rules it out in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/strong\u003E appears as small gram negative coccobacilli, not diplococci. While it is also an encapsulated organism that can cause severe infection in asplenic patients, the microscopy findings are inconsistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EListeria monocytogenes\u003C/strong\u003E appears as gram positive rods on microscopy. It typically affects the elderly, pregnant women, or immunocompromised patients, and is not an encapsulated organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/strong\u003E appears as gram negative rods on microscopy. It is primarily a cause of meningitis in neonates rather than adults and is not an encapsulated organism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe characteristic appearance of gram negative diplococci, combined with the clinical presentation and patient\u0027s asplenic state, makes \u003Cem\u003EN. meningitidis\u003C/em\u003E the most likely causative organism. This diagnosis warrants immediate notification to public health authorities and prophylaxis for close contacts. The case also highlights the importance of vaccination against encapsulated organisms and antibiotic prophylaxis in post-splenectomy patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gram negative diplococci on CSF microscopy in meningitis is highly suggestive of Neisseria meningitidis infection.","Post-splenectomy patients are at increased risk of infection with encapsulated organisms including Neisseria meningitidis.","Early recognition of meningococcal meningitis is crucial as mortality increases with delayed treatment."],"references":["Ram S, Lewis LA, Rice PA. Infections of people with complement deficiencies and patients who have undergone splenectomy. Clin Microbiol Rev. 2010;23(4):740-780. doi:10.1128/CMR.00048-09","Beaman MH. Community-acquired acute meningitis and encephalitis: a narrative review. Med J Aust. 2018;209(10):449-454. doi:10.5694/mja17.01073"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14620"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-26T16:53:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-26T16:55:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7313"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57510"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":